## Repo Purpose
{{ if eq .Kind "fullstack" }}
- Fullstack project split into a Go backend and a separate frontend application.
- Top-level layout:
	- `backend/`: the RonyKIT Go workspace (`go.work`). Run Go commands and `ronyup setup feature` from here.
	- `frontend/`: the web/mobile application (framework-agnostic; initialize with your stack of choice).
	- `devops/`: Kubernetes dev infrastructure via `devops/devbox/` (`make devbox-up` from `backend/`).
	- `docs/`: design documents (SRS/SDD) and guides (shared, stays at root).
	- `.ai/`, `.agents/`, `.cursor/`, `AGENTS.md`: AI assistant config (shared, stays at root).
- Inside `backend/`:
	- `bundles.yaml`: executable bundle manifest (default `service` = all-in-one dev binary).
	- `cmd/runner`: shared bootstrap for every executable.
	- `cmd/service`: default all-in-one dev executable; additional bundles under `cmd/<name>/`.
	- `feature/`: business modules.
	- `pkg/`: shared libraries (cross-module, business-agnostic).
{{- else if eq .Kind "frontend" }}
- Frontend-only project: a web/mobile application with shared AI assistant config.
- Top-level layout:
	- `frontend/`: the web/mobile application(s) (framework-agnostic; initialize with your stack of choice).
	- `docs/`: design documents (frontend design) and guides.
	- `.ai/`, `.agents/`, `.cursor/`, `AGENTS.md`: AI assistant config.
- There is no Go backend in this workspace; talk to external/back-end services over their HTTP/OpenAPI APIs.
{{- else }}
- Go workspace for RonyKIT services.
- Main folders in generated workspaces:
	- `bundles.yaml`: executable bundle manifest (default `service` = all-in-one dev binary).
	- `cmd/runner`: shared bootstrap for every executable.
	- `cmd/service`: default all-in-one dev executable; additional bundles under `cmd/<name>/`.
	- `feature/`: business modules.
	- `pkg/`: shared libraries (cross-module, business-agnostic).
	- `devops/`: `devops/devbox/` Helmfile-managed services on Kubernetes (`make devbox-up`).
{{- end }}

## Upgrading from an older ronyup

If this workspace was created before executable bundles, run once from the Go workspace root **or** the fullstack repository root:

```bash
ronyup setup migrate bundles
ronyup setup sync --only backend
```

See MCP `migrate_bundles` and `architecture/executable-bundles`.

## Mandatory gates (do these first, no matter what is asked)

These gates apply to **every** request ÔÇö even quick edits, prototypes, or "just
write the code" asks. Do not skip them unless the user explicitly tells you to.
{{- if eq .Kind "frontend" }}

1. **Clarify frontend topology before any frontend work.** Do **not** assume a
   single frontend app. Before creating or modifying anything under `frontend/`,
   ask the user whether there is **one** app or **multiple**. For multiple apps,
   each lives in its own directory (`frontend/<app-name>/`); confirm which app a
   change targets (and its name/stack when initializing a new one).
2. **Frontend design is document-first.** Before running `create-next-app`,
   `create vite`, or writing UI, ask aesthetic/design questions and write
   `docs/design/<app>-frontend-design.md` (`web` for a single app at `frontend/`).
   Read skills `frontend-design`, `design-tokens`, `typography` and MCP prompt
   `design-frontend`. Write with `status: draft`; only the **user** sets
   `status: approved`. This is enforced: `frontend/verify.sh` refuses to pass
   until the approved design doc exists.
{{- else if eq .Kind "fullstack" }}

1. **Backend features are document-first.** Before scaffolding or writing code
   for any new or changed service feature, write a Software Requirements
   Specification (SRS) and a Software Design Description (SDD) and get user
   approval:
   - `docs/design/<feature>-srs.md`, then `docs/design/<feature>-sdd.md`.
   - Use the MCP prompts `design-new-service` (full flow) or `write-srs` /
     `write-sdd`, and read `knowledge://ronyup/architecture/design-documents`.
   - Write each with `status: draft`; only the **user** sets `status: approved`.
     Never approve on the user's behalf.
   - This is enforced: `scaffold_feature` refuses to run until both documents
     exist and are `status: approved`.
2. **Clarify frontend topology before any frontend work.** Do **not** assume a
   single frontend app. Before creating or modifying anything under `frontend/`,
   ask the user:
   - Is there **one** frontend app or **multiple**?
   - For multiple apps, each app lives in its own directory
     (`frontend/<app-name>/`); confirm which app this change targets (and its
     name/stack when initializing a new one).
   - Only proceed once the target app and layout are confirmed.
3. **Frontend design is document-first.** Before running `create-next-app`,
   `create vite`, or writing UI, ask aesthetic/design questions and write
   `docs/design/<app>-frontend-design.md` (`web` for a single app at `frontend/`).
   Read skills `frontend-design`, `design-tokens`, `typography` and MCP prompt
   `design-frontend`. Write with `status: draft`; only the **user** sets
   `status: approved`. This is enforced: `frontend/verify.sh` refuses to pass
   until the approved design doc exists.
4. **Repo integration tests are mandatory.** Every method on every repository
   port in `internal/repo/port.go` needs an `internal/repo/integration_test/`
   test using `x/testkit` (happy path, not-found, conflict) that you **run** and
   confirm passes. Read MCP `architecture/integration-tests` and skill `go-testing`.
5. **App unit tests are mandatory.** Every exported method on `internal/app.App`
   needs a unit test in `internal/app/*_test.go`.
6. **Backend verify gate.** Before reporting backend feature work done, run
   `make verify` from `backend/`. This is **enforced**: `.cursor/hooks/backend-verify.sh`
   re-runs `verify.sh` when feature code changes and loops you back to fix failures.
   Test coverage is always enforced; the repo integration tests only **run** when
   Docker is available (otherwise the gate warns) ÔÇö so run `make verify` with
   Docker up before merging.
{{- else }}

1. **Backend features are document-first.** Before scaffolding or writing code
   for any new or changed service feature, write a Software Requirements
   Specification (SRS) and a Software Design Description (SDD) and get user
   approval:
   - `docs/design/<feature>-srs.md`, then `docs/design/<feature>-sdd.md`.
   - Use the MCP prompts `design-new-service` (full flow) or `write-srs` /
     `write-sdd`, and read `knowledge://ronyup/architecture/design-documents`.
   - Write each with `status: draft`; only the **user** sets `status: approved`.
     Never approve on the user's behalf.
   - This is enforced: `scaffold_feature` refuses to run until both documents
     exist and are `status: approved`.
2. **Repo integration tests are mandatory.** Every method on every repository
   port in `internal/repo/port.go` needs an `internal/repo/integration_test/`
   test using `x/testkit` (happy path, not-found, conflict) that you **run** and
   confirm passes. Read MCP `architecture/integration-tests` and skill `go-testing`.
3. **App unit tests are mandatory.** Every exported method on `internal/app.App`
   needs a unit test in `internal/app/*_test.go`.
4. **Backend verify gate.** Before reporting backend feature work done, run
   `make verify`. This is **enforced**: `.cursor/hooks/backend-verify.sh`
   re-runs `verify.sh` when feature code changes and loops you back to fix failures.
   Test coverage is always enforced; the repo integration tests only **run** when
   Docker is available (otherwise the gate warns) ÔÇö so run `make verify` with
   Docker up before merging.
{{- end }}
{{- if ne .Kind "backend" }}

## Frontend delivery ÔÇö verify yourself, don't hand back

Frontend work is **not done** when the code is written ÔÇö it is done when it
runs clean. Close the loop yourself; do **not** ask the user to run the app,
report errors back to you, or confirm that a fix worked.

- **Run the autonomous verify-and-fix loop** before reporting completion. The
  canonical gate is `make -C frontend verify` (equivalently
  `bash frontend/verify.sh`); it runs typecheck, lint, build, test,
  `build-storybook`, and the stories-coverage check for every app under
  `frontend/`. Read the full output, fix every error and meaningful warning,
  then **re-run the gate**. Repeat until it passes. Only stop and ask the user
  if you are genuinely blocked (missing secret, ambiguous product decision) ÔÇö
  not for ordinary type/lint/test/build failures.
- This is **enforced**: a Cursor `stop` hook (`.cursor/hooks/frontend-verify.sh`)
  re-runs `frontend/verify.sh` whenever you touch `frontend/` and loops you back
  to fix any failures before the turn can complete.
- **State results with evidence** (the command and its passing output). Never
  claim "done", "fixed", or "should work" without a fresh passing run.
- **Stories are mandatory.** Every new or changed reusable UI component ships a
  co-located Storybook story (`Button.tsx` Ôćĺ `Button.stories.tsx`) in the same
  change, covering its states/variants via `args`. A component without an
  up-to-date story is not done; create the story without being asked, and
  verify with `pnpm build-storybook`.
- Use the installed frontend skills (`frontend-design`, `design-tokens`,
  `typography`, `storybook`, `frontend-testing`, `nextjs-modern`, `shadcn`,
  `dashboard-ui`, `webmcp`, `ux-quality`, `verification-before-completion`) ÔÇö read their
  SKILL.md files per the routing table above.
{{- end }}

## Core Rules

- Keep changes scoped to the requested task.
- Do not edit unrelated files.
- Prefer targeted changes over broad refactors.
- Do not run destructive git operations.
- Run focused checks first, then broader checks.
{{- if ne .Kind "frontend" }}

## Package Selection (mandatory)

- Before hand-rolling a utility or importing a stdlib/third-party package, use the RonyKIT equivalent. The authoritative map is the MCP
  resource `knowledge://ronyup/architecture/package-selection`.
- Common helpers (IDs, JSON/byte casts, stringÔćönumber, case transforms, slice/map ops) Ôćĺ `x/rkit`. Logging Ôćĺ `x/telemetry/logkit`. Config Ôćĺ
  `x/settings`. DI Ôćĺ `x/di` + `uber/fx`. Errors Ôćĺ `rony/errs`. DB/Redis/S3 Ôćĺ `x/datasource`. Cache Ôćĺ `x/cache`. Rate limiting Ôćĺ
  `x/ratelimit`. Batching Ôćĺ `x/batch`. Pools Ôćĺ `x/p`.
- Durable workflows: use the `flow` package only ÔÇö never import `go.temporal.io/sdk` directly.
- The backend `.golangci.yml` enforces this with `depguard`; a forbidden-import lint failure is a design violation, not a formatting nit.

## Architecture Conventions

- Keep transport concerns in `api/` and business logic in `internal/app/`.
- Keep handlers thin; delegate business behavior to app use-cases.
- Define ports in `internal/repo/port.go`.
- Default repository/storage stack is Postgres + `sqlc`.
- Keep adapter implementations in `internal/repo/v0/` (and use other data stacks only when explicitly requested).
- Keep module config in `internal/settings/`.
- After API contract changes, run `make gen-stub` in that feature module.
- For inter-service calls, use generated stubs from `feature/*/stub/*` instead of hand-written clients.
- Shared utilities belong in `pkg/` and should not depend on feature business logic.

## Service Design Pattern

For a new feature module:

- Add/adjust contracts in `api/service.go`.
- Implement use-cases in `internal/app/app.go` (and split files as it grows).
- Add persistence interfaces in `internal/repo/port.go`.
- Implement datastore integration in `internal/repo/v0/adapter.go`.
- Update settings and config templates when new dependencies are introduced.

## Suggested Workflow

1. Write and get approval for the SRS and SDD (`docs/design/<feature>-srs.md`,
   `docs/design/<feature>-sdd.md`) ÔÇö see "Mandatory gates" above. Do not skip.
{{- if eq .Kind "fullstack" }}
2. Scaffold feature (from `backend/`): `ronyup setup feature --featureDir <dir> --featureName <name> --template service`
{{- else }}
2. Scaffold feature: `ronyup setup feature --featureDir <dir> --featureName <name> --template service`
{{- end }}
3. Implement contracts and app use-cases.
4. Run `make gen-stub` in the feature module after contract updates.
5. In other service modules, consume the generated stubs for client calls.
6. Add tests for app and API behavior; **run** `make verify` to confirm repo
   integration tests and app unit tests pass.
7. Run:
	- `make tidy`
	- `make lint`
	- `make test`
{{- end }}

## Quality Expectations
{{- if eq .Kind "frontend" }}

- Responsive down to mobile (Ôëą360px); no overflow or broken layout.
- Accessible: visible keyboard focus, semantic HTML, labelled controls; respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.
- Use semantic design tokens (no scattered raw hex/px); derive values from the approved design doc.
- Every reusable UI component ships a co-located Storybook story.
- `typecheck`, `lint`, `build`, and `test` pass via `frontend/verify.sh` before reporting done.
{{- else }}

- Idempotent behavior for retryable operations.
- Validate input at API boundary.
- Keep domain naming consistent across API, app, repo, and settings.
{{- end }}
